All I've done is-- because you
can't see this too well--

00:21:49.790 --> 00:21:52.180
taken some segments out of
here so we can talk about

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:54.510
them, specifically.

00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:55.770
You'll see the link
for that later.

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:56.610
Please use it.

00:21:56.610 --> 00:21:59.650
It's really useful.

00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:02.380
So the first thing we want to
do is create a new product,

00:22:02.380 --> 00:22:04.290
upload a product to
Google Shopping.

00:22:04.290 --> 00:22:06.270
And this is probably the
most common use case.

00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:07.070
How do we do that?

00:22:07.070 --> 00:22:10.580
Well, we make a POST request, so
inserting products, always

00:22:10.580 --> 00:22:15.130
a POST request. And we make it
to the product URI, the feed

00:22:15.130 --> 00:22:16.380
URI for that merchant.

00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:22.110
You can also see that we pass
a couple of extra headers.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:24.350
The first one is the
authorization header.

00:22:24.350 --> 00:22:26.510
Now, all requests for this
need to be authorized.

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:30.040
We're using AuthSub here, but
