as whatever you like as long

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:00.020
as it's UTF-8.

00:23:00.020 --> 00:23:02.370
No, no, as whatever you like.

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:05.630
And then you see the entry
element that we have. We've

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:06.840
got a few namespaces.

00:23:06.840 --> 00:23:09.410
I've left some out for brevity
and I've actually left out

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:10.510
some required fields here.

00:23:10.510 --> 00:23:13.080
So what you would have is
slightly bigger than this.

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:17.830
But you can see the title, the
Content-Type text, the SCID

00:23:17.830 --> 00:23:22.490
element, which is the SKU, the
condition element, the price,

00:23:22.490 --> 00:23:23.990
which has the units
of currency.

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:27.410
The unit is required, and then
some tax information.

00:23:27.410 --> 00:23:29.740
Now tax is specifically
localizable.

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:32.710
You can say, I want the tax in
California to be such and

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:36.200
such, or I want the tax in the
zip code to be such and such,

00:23:36.200 --> 00:23:38.830
or in this city to be
however you like.

00:23:38.830 --> 00:23:44.510
So you can specify arbitrarily
complex tax rules there.

00:23:44.510 --> 00:23:45.600
And what do we get back?

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:47.780
Well, we've just sent
the product.

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:49.790
We've created a new product.

00:23:49.790 --> 00:23:50.320
Brilliant.

00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:53.060
And so we get back a
201 response, which

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:54.510
means you've created.

00:23:54.510 --> 00:23:55.320
This is interesting.

00:23:55.320 --> 00:23:58.090
From a REST point of view, not
only have we created a new

00:23:58.090 --> 00:24:02.400
product, we've created a new
REST resource, a new place

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:03.940
where you can do stuff.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:06.360
And so we get back
in the headers--

00:24:06.360 --> 00:24:11.080
a location header which shows
us our new resource

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:12.860
with our new URI.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:15.692
So you can store that and use
that if you want to update the

00:24:15.692 --> 00:24:17.910
information later.

00:24:17.910 --> 00:24:20.820
And with that, we get a response
back that is an echo

00:24:20.820 --> 00:24:23.890
of our original request. So it
tells us that the fields we've

00:24:23.890 --> 00:24:25.710
added have been successful.

00:24:25.710 --> 00:24:29.450
And with a few others added,
such as, the published, which

00:24:29.450 --> 00:24:31.250
tells us that it's been
published and the date and

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:34.660
time, the APP edited,
that's the Atom

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:38.690
Publishing Protocol namespace.

00:24:38.690 --> 00:24:41.080
I've added here a couple of
elements that weren't in the

00:24:41.080 --> 00:24:44.110
original POST request, which we
would have needed to have.

00:24:44.110 --> 00:24:46.990
And there you see, really
important, the link REL equals

00:24:46.990 --> 00:24:51.130
alternate element that is the
landing page for this product.

00:24:51.130 --> 00:24:52.880
This is the page that
people would go to.

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:55.690
So that's inserting products,
I think the

00:24:55.690 --> 00:24:57.070
most common use case.

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:58.350
As you'll see, you
can use this for

00:24:58.350 --> 00:24:59.990
updating products as well.

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:02.800
But I'm just going to show you
how to update a product.

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:05.630
Now this time, instead of doing
a POST request, we do a

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:10.140
PUT request to the specific
product URI, which is there,

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:12.690
and the same as the product URI
we just got back when we

00:25:12.690 --> 00:25:13.740
created it.

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:15.820
Again, it needs to be authorized
and we need to

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:18.750
provide the Content-Type
header.

00:25:18.750 --> 00:25:22.720
We send exactly the same body,
but it's not exactly the same

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:25.565
because you might be keen, and
notice that I've gone on sale

00:25:25.565 --> 00:25:27.480
and I've reduced my
price slightly.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:30.270
So if I want to update a
product, I send exactly the

00:25:30.270 --> 00:25:33.800
same as I would to insert
a new product with the

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:35.900
additional information, but
this time I send it to the

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:40.760
specific product URI with
a PUT request. And

00:25:40.760 --> 00:25:42.160
we get back a 200.

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:43.430
We haven't created
anything new.

00:25:43.430 --> 00:25:44.380
We've just updated.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:48.530
It's just a simple 200 with,
again, the information that we

00:25:48.530 --> 00:25:51.600
echoed and we got back.

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:53.940
The third important use case
is deleting products.

00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:54.970
Well, that's really easy.

00:25:54.970 --> 00:25:56.850
We don't send anything,
you really you get

00:25:56.850 --> 00:25:58.680
anything back, as a body.

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:02.430
You just send a delete request
to the specific product

00:26:02.430 --> 00:26:05.030
endpoint, and you just get
the response back.

00:26:05.030 --> 00:26:06.300
And that's how you
delete a product.

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:12.060
One of our most important
features for this API is that

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:14.000
we support batch processing.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:18.990
Now a batch is a set of
operations, each one with a

00:26:18.990 --> 00:26:20.970
project associated with it.

00:26:20.970 --> 00:26:25.090
So by operation, I mean you can
insert product A, you can

00:26:25.090 --> 00:26:28.250
update product B, you can
delete product C.

00:26:28.250 --> 00:26:31.330
So each product in a feed
comes with an operation.

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:34.340
And the advantage of that is you
can put, firstly, hundreds

00:26:34.340 --> 00:26:38.640
in a single request. And so you
just saved the amount of

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:39.850
requests you have to make.

00:26:39.850 --> 00:26:41.990
And that can go up to a megabyte
in size which is

00:26:41.990 --> 00:26:45.840
gzipped, so we'll see a little
example of that.

00:26:45.840 --> 00:26:48.620
But if you're like most
merchants-- and most merchants

00:26:48.620 --> 00:26:51.320
don't have 10 or 15 products,
they have hundreds and

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:53.010
hundreds of thousands
of products.

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:54.650
Some merchants here
have hundreds

00:26:54.650 --> 00:26:56.620
of millions of products.

00:26:56.620 --> 00:27:01.320
So if you batch them, that's
really advantageous for you

00:27:01.320 --> 00:27:03.730
because you make
fewer requests.

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:06.750
Also say we get individual
responses for each batch

00:27:06.750 --> 00:27:09.640
operation, so you will know
which ones succeed and you

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:11.940
will know which ones fail, and
you will get the error

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:13.370
information that you need.

00:27:13.370 --> 00:27:16.710
Let's have a look at one.

00:27:16.710 --> 00:27:21.080
All batch requests are a POST to
the batch URI, which is the

00:27:21.080 --> 00:27:23.640
product feed with the
word batch attached

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:24.210
on the end of it.

00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:25.950
So they're all POSTs, it doesn't
matter what kind of

00:27:25.950 --> 00:27:28.690
operation, because you will
specify the type of operation

00:27:28.690 --> 00:27:30.925
in the entries themselves.

00:27:33.450 --> 00:27:37.750
And here's a batch body with
just one operation in there,

00:27:37.750 --> 00:27:40.750
so imagine there could
be hundreds in there.

00:27:40.750 --> 00:27:44.470
Again, it's a feed at the top
level and its a simple entry

00:27:44.470 --> 00:27:46.590
exactly like our other entry.

00:27:46.590 --> 00:27:50.140
And my laser light is gone.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:52.270
You can see then there's
the batch element.

00:27:52.270 --> 00:27:56.580
And that batch element has
an operation type and

00:27:56.580 --> 00:27:58.090
that type is insert.

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:03.070
So this will insert this
product, if we send the batch.

00:28:03.070 --> 00:28:04.820
And when we send the batch,
we're always going to get a

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:08.190
200 back, even if we send a
hundred operations that were

00:28:08.190 --> 00:28:10.860
all complete garbage and none
of them succeeded, we will

00:28:10.860 --> 00:28:15.370
still get a 200 back because the
batch itself did succeed.

00:28:15.370 --> 00:28:16.980
And this is what the response
looks like.

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:19.920
Well, it's identical to our
other responses, but it does

00:28:19.920 --> 00:28:23.560
have the addition, firstly, of
the batch operations that we

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:27.090
had parsed and then,
importantly, the response code

00:28:27.090 --> 00:28:30.590
for that batch, which, in this
case, is the 201 created,

00:28:30.590 --> 00:28:33.820
identical to the response we
got back when we made the

00:28:33.820 --> 00:28:35.820
insert request. So
that's batching.

00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:39.960
I recommend you all use it if
you're uploading products.

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:41.830
We also have real
time updates.

00:28:41.830 --> 00:28:45.070
Now, normally, when you upload
a product to Google Product

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:47.600
Search, it takes a few hours.

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:49.380
You're thinking why, why does
that take a few hours?

00:28:49.380 --> 00:28:50.470
Well, we have to validate it.

00:28:50.470 --> 00:28:53.480
We have to make sure that the
page exists, the product is

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:56.000
accurate, the information is
accurate, because we can't

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.450
risk people putting false
information, or we don't want

00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:02.290
to risk that bad experience
for the user.

00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:04.350
So it takes a while to check.

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:07.490
But the really important
information, and that is the

00:29:07.490 --> 00:29:10.660
price and the quantity, as in
your inventory of the stock.

00:29:10.660 --> 00:29:13.990
If you change that, we have
a special fast track.

00:29:13.990 --> 00:29:15.300
So that means, within--

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:17.210
I've said five minutes but
it's actually shorter--

00:29:17.210 --> 00:29:20.800
so almost immediately, that
result will be reflected in

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:23.280
Product Search.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:25.615
That's really great because as
Nitin said, people like to

00:29:25.615 --> 00:29:27.810
know when the product's
in stock.

00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:29.290
In fact, they need to know.

00:29:29.290 --> 00:29:31.910
So it gives them the most
accurate information as

00:29:31.910 --> 00:29:34.140
quickly as possible, and people
are more likely to buy

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:36.310
stuff off you.

00:29:36.310 --> 00:29:37.810
We also have other features.

00:29:37.810 --> 00:29:39.090
I'm just going to race
through this.

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:42.680
Firstly, inserts for existing
items are updates.

00:29:42.680 --> 00:29:46.370
So if you try and insert the
same item twice, and by the

00:29:46.370 --> 00:29:50.140
same item, using that four part
ID, the second time won't

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:53.850
create a new item, it will
merely update the old item.

00:29:53.850 --> 00:29:58.255
OK, so that's the quickest
way to update an item.

00:29:58.255 --> 00:30:01.510
The difference with a normal
update is that, in a normal

00:30:01.510 --> 00:30:04.110
update, if the product doesn't
exist, you'll get an error.

00:30:04.110 --> 00:30:06.360
You can't update a product that
doesn't exist. Whereas

00:30:06.360 --> 00:30:09.310
here, it would just go on and
create the product, so this is

00:30:09.310 --> 00:30:12.290
the quickest way of updating
your product information.

00:30:12.290 --> 00:30:16.110
We also have data feed API, not
to mention that you can

